*># $$X \in \mathfrak R$$
*># $$A \in \mathfrak R \implies X\setminus A \in \mathfrak R$$
*># $$A_n \in \mathfrak R \implies \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty A_n \in \mathfrak R$$


* $$(X, \mathfrak R)$$ then called a ''Measurable Space''. Members of $$\mathfrak R$$ are called ''Measurable Sets''

!! MeasurableMap
* let $$f: (X, \mathfrak R) \to (Y, \tau)$$, X - measurable space, Y - TopologicalSpace. $$f$$ is a ''Measurable Map'' iff

*> $$\forall V \in \tau :\; f^{-1}(V) \in \mathfrak R$$

* $$s$$ is a ''Simple Measurable Map'' iff its range $$s(X)$$ is finite

